      "text": "1. MCAT tests have a substantial correlation with performance in medical school. \n2. Performance in medical school has a substantial correlation with various measures of physician competence. \n3. Black scores on the MCAT for the last four decades have been substantially lower than white/asian scores. Around an SD or more. \n4. Black mean performance as physicians on various measures of competence have been lower than white/Asian performance. \n\nNone of the first three assertions can be empirically denied. The evidence is too consistent and replicable. \n\nThe fourth assertion is not only empirically undeniable. It is logically inevitable.",
      "text_resolved": "1. MCAT tests have a substantial correlation with performance in medical school. \n2. Performance in medical school has a substantial correlation with various measures of physician competence. \n3. Black scores on the MCAT for the last four decades have been substantially lower than white/asian scores. Around an SD or more. \n4. Black mean performance as physicians on various measures of competence have been lower than white/Asian performance. \n\nNone of the first three assertions can be empirically denied. The evidence is too consistent and replicable. \n\nThe fourth assertion is not only empirically undeniable. It is logically inevitable.",
